Food debt to European inflation
The main reason for the increase in inflation measured in the euro area was the rapidly rising food prices.
In the 13 eurozone countries, the price increase was higher than expected in November - after 2.6 percent in October, an annual inflation rate of 3.1 percent was recorded, as reported by the EU Statistical Office in Luxembourg.
Official forecasts have been expected of only 3 percent, reported Bloomberg.
In contrast to the American, British, and Canadian central banks, the European Central Bank (ECB) has not lowered the latter. According to its discretion, the reduction in interest rates would favour the rise in commodity prices and the slight fall in unemployment as a result of an inflation spiral.
The ECB is committed to keeping the inflation rate below two percent, or at least short on the two-percent mark.
According to an analyst, the ECB is in the Zwickmühle: inflation must be "agreed" in order to exclude later action needs.
At 3.3 per cent, the inflation rate reached a 12-year record high in Germany in November; in Spain the rate climbed from 3.6 per cent to 4.1 per cent.
Responsible for the rise in inflation in the euro area were the rise in food and energy prices.
The MATIF wheat listings rose by 88 percent, and the price for soybeans also reached a record high since 1973.
Food oil and dairy products also cost significantly in 2007.
The world market price for crude oil rose by 52 percent this year - last month the price per barrel of black gold reached nearly 100 US dollars.
According to the ECB, inflation will rise from 2.1 to 2.5 percent in 2008, but in 2009 it is expected to decrease to 1.9 percent.
For the next 3-4 months, analysts expect a 3-percent inflation rate, but the annual average rate is 2.1 percent.
For 2008, experts expect the ECB to reduce interest rates twice.
