In many places, disinfectants are saved
Today, more than a thousand infections have been recorded in hospitals due to improper use of antibiotics.
The hygienic conditions in the hospitals, the overcrowding of the beds, the overload of the staff - all factors that are not directly relevant to the control of the infections, according to the chief physician of the National Epidemiology Centre.
In many places the disinfectants are also saved.
In the traumatology department of János Hospital a MRSA infection has recently been diagnosed.
The antibiotic-resistant bacterium was found in a male patient who was hospitalized after a severe accident.
The patient was isolated.
At the beginning of the year there was already a similar infection here.
The injured one of a severe car accident was released from the hospital, but a little later the man had to return with an MRSA infection. An important operation has not been performed since because of the bacterium that is still in the patient’s body.
By 10 December of this year, infections caused by multi-resistant pathogens were reported to the National Nosocomials Surveillance System, according to the chief physician of the National Epidemiology Centre, Karolina Böröcz.
So many infections caused by multi-resistant pathogens have been recorded in hospitals with certainty, but the dark rate is likely to be higher.
Approximately two thirds of infections (683 cases) were triggered by MRSA, the Staphylococcus aureus resistant to methicillin-oxacilline.
The Staphylococcus aureus (SA) bacteria carries about a third of the people in their nose without causing a disease.
SA-related infections (such as inflammation of the throat, inflammation of the almonds, inflammation of the skin or wounds) usually respond well to antibiotics, they are well curable.
However, if the drugs are used too high or improperly, antibiotic resistant from the well-responsive bacteria, which spread rapidly in hospitals under appropriate conditions.
Especially in patients with weakened, or permanently poor immune system functioning, but also in elderly, or patients with low body weight, these bacteria can cause severe infections, such as wound infection or blood poisoning, i.e. sepsis.
According to the medical director of Jáno's hospital, the MRSA infection is nothing special, such incidents are part of the hospital's everyday life.
If the infection is not to be confused with the epidemic, Tibor Nyulasi - MRSA told us there is no place where it is not sought.
Antibiotic resistance
"Such patients are isolated, the care staff wear rubber gloves and masks in the care, and we have the antibiotics necessary for the treatment" - according to Tibor Nyulasi.
Although patients are examined on MRSA, an infection cannot be avoided at all.
Sample withdrawals too rare
The majority of the infections caused by MRSA in hospitals would be avoidable, but the current prevailing conditions and circumstances would be unfavourable to curbing the development or spread of the multi-resistant pathogen, says Karolina Böröcz.
After this infection occurs mainly in hospitals and nursing homes, the hospital staff should examine the patients who have received it and immediately isolate MRSA-infected patients.
However, microbiological sampling is not practised so often in the Hungarian hospitals.
Not least because there are no subsidies for this investigation on the part of the state sickness fund.
Thus, most cases would not come to daylight until the patient has a noticeable MRSA infection, according to the medical director of the epidemiology centre.
The European Union has strongly recommended the appropriate use of antibiotics in human medicine, but there are also guidelines in Hungary for the treatment of certain infections and diseases.
Antibiotic therapies are supposed to be targeted, i.e. microbiological examinations are necessary in order to avoid resistance to the drug, but this directive is not always complied with by hospitals.
According to Karolina Böröcz, microbiological samples were even more rare among patients in the ambulatory, or in the primary care.
Saving in disinfectants
Scientific evidence proves that MRSA is transferred from one patient to the other by the nurse most frequently.
This is precisely why hand washing, or wearing gloves and masks is of great importance, but there are also significant deficiencies in this area in hospitals.
MRSA is transmitted by droplet infection or contact, but in the home hospitals there is not always the possibility to isolate the infected patient.
The rooms are often overcrowded, the beds stretched close to each other, although there should be a distance of at least 1.5 meters between them from an epidemiological point of view.
Unfortunately, as Karolina Böröcz continues to point out, in the less well funded hospitals, even the fact that disinfectants are saved, there are few caregivers, many patients - all factors that directly favour the development of infections.
Such infections are shown to be far less frequent, or may be stopped the further spread of the pathogen, where these protective measures are observed, says Karolina Böröcz.
Government programme against MRSA
Getting MRSA infections under control causes health insurance enormous costs, so they are being fought everywhere.
In England, for example, the prevention of MRSA and its containment were recorded in the government programme.
After first signs, the program is successful - as published data show, the tendency of MRSA infections in England is declining.
The European Centre for Disease Prevention (ECDC) has declared prevention of the emergence of multi-resistant pathogens (including MRSA), as well as prevention of infections in hospitals to be one of its priorities.
