Fodor and the Six Hungarian Percentages
As Environment Minister Gábor Fodor announced, the expert meetings will end on Tuesday, and the debate on the international climate regime after 2012 will continue by the ministers on Wednesday after the official opening.
Experts and politicians from 192 countries are consulting on the Bali Roadmap, which sets the emission reduction measures for the post-2012 period, that is, after the Kyoto Protocol expires.
At present, a heated debate is underway between industrial and developing countries.
The US has already signalled that they do not want to negotiate concrete figures, but they would be willing to reduce greenhouse gas emissions by 25-40 percent by 2020 compared to 1990.
The other major question of the conference is whether the industrialised countries are prepared to support developing countries financially and technologically, in addition to reducing emissions.
An agreement was also reached on support for developing countries.
The Adaptation Fund set out in the Kyoto Protocol is to be managed by a 16-member Council, expected at the UN Global Environmental Facility (GFF), as read in the "Piac és Profit".
Hungary's six percent
Environment Minister Gábor Fodor, in the name of Hungary, supports the EU's efforts to maintain its pioneering role in global climate action and to reach a new international agreement by 2009.
The Minister said that the EU will reduce greenhouse gas emissions by 20% by 2020 (measured at 1990 levels), regardless of whether the "Agreement after 2012" will be successful or not. The Union would even be prepared to use itself for a 30 percent reduction, provided that other major industrial states in the world, or developing countries, are also prepared to fulfil their commitments in a strong and responsible manner.
Gábor Fodor stressed that the target of the countries that joined the Kyoto Protocol in 1997 was a reduction of only 5.2 percent, whereas the EU had already committed itself to a decrease of 8% with its then 15 member states.
The requirement for Hungary is to reduce greenhouse gas emissions by 6% compared to 1985-87 - a requirement that the country will be able to meet, as is stated in the Environmental Ministry's press release.
The commitment is high on Bali - after all, the long-term international climate policy agreement must be completed within two years, otherwise it would certainly enter into force only after 2012. In this case, the Kyoto Protocol reduction project would not follow a new international emission reduction system, the importance of which has also been highlighted by the IPCC, the international scientific climate change committee of the UN in its recent report, with the Nobel Peace Prize.
This would delay the reduction of emissions, and the increase in the average temperature of the earth by more than 2°C would be unavoidable, which, according to scientists, would result in extremely serious and irreparable consequences.
