A heavy reminder
After more than 60 years of confidential treatment, the Nazi archives of Bad Arolsen, which document the fate of 17.5 million victims of the Hitler regime, are now freely accessible.
The 47 million documents of the archive, which are housed in Bad Arolsen at a total length of 27 km, have not been available until now, except with a humanitarian intention, i.e. individual and named, i.e. on the question of a former victim or his family members.
In May 2006, the eleven States entrusted with their administration - including Germany, France, Israel and the United States - agreed to make them accessible to researchers and historians.
After the ratification process of this Decision has been completed, the opening has been valid since yesterday.
Clues Down
The access of historians to Bad Arolsen will enable research to be carried out, especially on the deportations of prisoners, the inmates of the concentration camps and the state of health of forced workers, explains Reto Masters, head of this archive, which is managed by the International Committee of the Red Cross (CICR).
Until recently, several states, including Germany, were opposed to making these name-related documents available to the public, due to the delicate nature of certain information.
For example, the alleged homosexuality or the mental disability of some deportation victims.
The prisoners' lists of the concentration camps or the arrest warrants issued by the Gestapo had been assembled after the war for a practical reason: to find civilians who had been deported or subjected to forced labour, and to provide them with any evidence of their arrest, so as to pave the way for their compensation.
Today, more than 300 permanent tens of thousands of personal inquiries are still being handled in Bad Arolsen.
Nevertheless, part of the scientific community shows only a limited interest in access to Bad Arolsen.
There is nothing fundamentally new in these documents, said Pr. Wolfgang Benz, Head of the Research Centre for Anti-Semitism at the Technical University of Berlin, 2006.
