New fears about natural gas dispute between Russia and Ukraine
A new price dispute between Ukraine and Russia increases the risk of affecting Russian exports of fuel to Western Europe.
The majority of Russian gas exports to the European Union (EU) are managed by Ukraine and each dispute between the two nations is closely observed.
Kiev has warned that if Moscow increases the price it has to pay for natural gas, it will charge higher transit fees from Russia.
A previous conflict between the two states last year reduced deliveries to the EU countries.
The recent dispute between Kiev and Moscow is taking place at a time when the Ukrainian government and the Russian state gas monopoly Gazprom are trying to reach an agreement on how much Ukraine must pay for Russian natural gas in 2008.
According to Gazprom, Ukraine needs to be calculated more because the Group has agreed to pay up to 50% in addition to natural gas from neighboring Turkmenistan.
Analysts say that this could mean that Ukraine has to pay 40% more for Gazprom imports.
"It is important for us to use our arguments as one of the most important gas transit states in discussions," said the Minister of Economic Affairs of Ukraine Anatoli Kinakh of the news agency Reuters.
"The changing natural gas prices should undoubtedly be linked to our arguments regarding the level of transit fees [to Western Europe] over Ukraine."
In the last major natural gas dispute between Moscow and Kiev in January 2006, Gazprom reduced deliveries to Ukraine.
This subsequently led to a case of exports to Western Europe, which dramatically increased prices.
Russian gas constitutes a quarter of the supply of the European Union.
Russia has the largest gas deposits in the world, but much of it remains underdeveloped.
The result is that Gazprom complements its own stocks of gas from Turkmenistan and other Central Asian former Soviet nations.
NHS "must control foreign workers"
The Scottish State Health Service must improve checks on the criminal records for workers from outside Europe, said one member of the control body outside.
The recommendation of the principal financial controller Robert Black came after a foreign doctor was brought to Scotland in conjunction with the attack on Glasgow Airport in June.
Black also expressed concern that the Scottish state health service had no precise ideas about the number of its foreign employees.
But his report pointed out that other important controls were carried out correctly in the case of a sample of five health authorities.
The principal financial controller examined staff recruited outside the countries of the European Economic Area following the attack on Glasgow airport.
Bilal Abdullah, 28, an Iraqi doctor at the Royal Alexandra Hospital in Paisley, was arrested at the airport after an off-road car was driven through the doors of the main airport terminal.
He was one of three doctors who appeared in a video transmission at Old Bailey in October and was burdened with the alleged car bomb attack in Great Britain.
It is expected that the State Health Service will carry out checks in advance of the recruitment of foreign staff to ensure that they have the necessary qualifications, experience and authorisation to work in the United Kingdom.
Although health authorities use Disclosure Scotland to review criminal records, the Agency does not have the competence to obtain this information outside the UK.
The report of the auditors now states, in addition to other recommendations, that the Executive Board should take up guidelines for the collection of criminal records which help employers in controlling different countries.
"Although we have found evidence of these controls in some personnel documents, they have not been routinely carried out," the report noted.
Black said that the Scottish health authorities would follow their research guidelines with a high degree before employment, but added: "Our report shows areas in which the system can be improved to ensure that accurate information on the number of foreign health professionals is available."
BMA Scotland President Dr. Peter Terry said it was "extremely unlikely" that investigations would identify people who could face future terrorist attacks in the run-up to the recruitment of potential NHS staff.
"The report says that present pre-selection tests by NHS Scotland are working well and it is not clear what added value the recommendations will provide," he said.
The Scottish health authorities say that they currently have 1,161 foreign employees, the vast majority of them doctors and nurses.
However, the financial controller warned that the number is likely to be higher, also because the boards had problems identifying those employees who are on leave for an indefinite period of time.
The investigation continued to establish that established control procedures have been observed by NHS authorities in Ayrshire, Arran, Grampian, Greater Glasgow and Clyde, Lanarkshire, and Lothian.
These include passport, work permit and qualification checks.
the Scottish Government is currently reviewing its policy and guidelines for pre-arrangement controls for foreign personnel in the NHS.
The health secretary Nicola Sturgeon said: "It was my concern to carry out this work in the face of the terrorist attack at Glasgow Airport."
It added that the Scottish Government, in conjunction with the health authorities, would take into account the recommendations of the report and ensure that the best practices in updated guidelines regarding the monitoring studies would reflect before all employees are employed, including those from abroad, whose publication is planned next month.
