These aren't Warhol's boxes.
Those who combine the concepts of Sweden and wooden chests think of Ikea, but not of Andy Warhol.
Isn't it?
Currently, in Sweden, fabricated wooden boxes throw dark shadows on Warhol's work directory.
Most of the Brillo boxes of the "type Stockholm" listed there are counterfeits.
After the Swedish newspaper "Expressen" had raised doubts about the authenticity of Andy Warhol's Briillo boxes in 1968, internal research in the Moderna Museet in Stockholm is now coming to a sobering conclusion: The six "Briillo-Boxes", which the former museum director Pontus Hultén has made as a gift to the Moderna Museet in 1995, are copies - and probably the majority of the more than a hundred more Briillo boxes from the "type Stockholm", which are in circulation on the international art market.
The prehistory is nestled, a confusing chain of artistic and curatorial productions.
In 1964, Warhol created his first "Brillo Boxes" in New York, painted wooden boxes based on the red-blue-white design of the cardboard cardboard of soap powder "Brillo".
An exhibition of his works at the Moderna Museet 1968 - with Warhol's consent - exhibited hundreds of Briillo boxes from cardboard: these were not from Warhol (for cost reasons) but were delivered directly from the Briillo-Cartonagenfabrik.
It was not works of art, it was their role models, it was just exhibits.
At the same time, Warhol probably granted permission in 1968 to produce a few Brillo wooden boxes in Sweden, which were not exhibited in the Moderna Museet.
Time witnesses now speak of around fifteen boxes, which have rightly entered the art and auction history as an authorized original andy-warhol-brillo boxes called "Type Stockholm".
Some of them have generated more than $100,000 on auctions.
The problem is that the legendary museum director Pontus Hultén later falsely claimed that it had been produced and exhibited around a hundred wooden boxes in Sweden in 1968, which Warhol had then left to him.
In fact, Hultén's 105 boxes were only produced in Malmö in 1990 for an exhibition in St. Petersburg.
At that time Warhol was already three years dead.
Lars Byström, chief conservator at the Moderna Museet, has also studied three Swedish private estates, two of which were manufactured in Stockholm in 1968: their press plates were first founded and embroidered, and then white oil paint was applied with a brush.
The structure of the 1990 copies, on the other hand, reveals that the colour was applied directly to the press plate with a painting roll without a foundation, and it is not an oil-, but an acrylic color.
"These boxes were not authorized by the artist and should be removed from the official list of Andy Warhol's Briillo Boxes", says the director of the Moderna Museet, Lars Nittve: "If the 'Andy Warhol Art Authentication Board' in New York does not come to a different conclusion, the Moderna Museet will classify the six boxes in its collection as copies/exhibition material."
In July, of course, the Authentication Board announced that it would proceed with the "serious accusations" raised in the case of soap powder boxes.
But since then, they have shrouded themselves in unforgivable silence.
